    title: "Pressure Injury Prevention: Braden & Bundles",
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Pressure Injury Prevention: Braden & Bundles", content: "The nurse practitioner evaluates and manages Pressure Injury Prevention: Braden & Bundles through systematic dermatological assessment and evidence-based dermatological pharmacotherapy. Assessment includes focused dermatological history (onset, distribution, pruritus, pain, aggravating/relieving factors, exposures, medication history, family history, occupational exposures), systematic skin examination using standardized morphological terminology (primary lesions: macule, patch, papule, plaque, nodule, vesicle, bulla, pustule, wheal, cyst; secondary lesions: scale, crust, erosion, ulcer, fissure, atrophy, scar, lichenification), and description of distribution pattern (generalized, localized, dermatomal, photodistributed, flexural, extensor). The NP applies diagnostic algorithms including dermoscopy for pigmented lesion evaluation (ABCDE criteria, dermoscopic features of melanoma versus benign nevi), KOH preparation for fungal infections, skin biopsy indication and technique (shave, punch, excisional), and patch testing referral for contact dermatitis. Pharmacotherapy selection is guided by diagnosis: topical corticosteroid potency matching (low potency for face/intertriginous areas, high potency for thick plaques on trunk/extremities), topical immunomodulators (tacrolimus, pimecrolimus for steroid-sparing therapy), antifungals (topical versus systemic based on extent and nail involvement), antibiotics for bacterial skin infections, and systemic immunomodulatory therapy for severe inflammatory dermatoses. The NP performs skin cancer screening, counsels on photoprotection, and determines dermatology referral criteria." },
